<Layout title="Recurrent Pregnancy Loss">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Recurrent Pregnancy Loss</h1>
			<p>Understanding, testing, and treatment options after multiple miscarriages.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>What is Recurrent Pregnancy Loss?</h2>
		<p>Recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL) is typically defined as two or more consecutive pregnancy losses before 20 weeks gestation. Some doctors use three or more as the threshold. It affects about 1-2% of couples trying to conceive.</p>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>When to seek evaluation:</strong> Most specialists recommend a full RPL workup after 2 consecutive losses, especially if you're over 35 or have other risk factors. Don't wait for a third loss to get answers.
		</div>

		<h2>Causes of Recurrent Loss</h2>
		<p>In about 50% of cases, no cause is found. When a cause is identified, common factors include:</p>

		<table>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Category</th>
					<th>Cause</th>
					<th>Frequency</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>Genetic/Chromosomal</td>
					<td>Embryo aneuploidy (random chromosomal errors)</td>
					<td>50-60% of losses</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Genetic/Chromosomal</td>
					<td>Parental balanced translocation</td>
					<td>2-5% of couples with RPL</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Uterine</td>
					<td>Uterine septum</td>
					<td>3-5%</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Uterine</td>
					<td>Fibroids (submucosal)</td>
					<td>5-10%</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Uterine</td>
					<td>Asherman's syndrome (scarring)</td>
					<td>5%</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Thrombophilia</td>
					<td>Antiphospholipid syndrome (APS)</td>
					<td>5-15%</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Thrombophilia</td>
					<td>Inherited clotting disorders</td>
					<td>5-10%</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Endocrine</td>
					<td>Thyroid dysfunction</td>
					<td>5-10%</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Endocrine</td>
					<td>Uncontrolled diabetes</td>
					<td>Variable</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Endocrine</td>
					<td>Low progesterone / luteal phase defect</td>
					<td>Debated</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Immune</td>
					<td>Natural killer cell abnormalities</td>
					<td>Controversial</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Unexplained</td>
					<td>No identifiable cause</td>
					<td>50%</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<h2>RPL Testing Workup</h2>

		<h3>Standard Testing (Recommended)</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<h4>Genetic Testing</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Karyotype (both partners):</strong> Blood test to check for balanced translocations or other chromosomal rearrangements</li>
				<li><strong>Products of conception (POC) testing:</strong> Genetic analysis of miscarriage tissue to determine if chromosomal abnormality caused the loss</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $200-$500 per karyotype; $500-$1,500 for POC testing</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Uterine Evaluation</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Transvaginal ultrasound:</strong> Basic uterine assessment</li>
				<li><strong>Saline sonogram (SIS):</strong> Saline-enhanced ultrasound to see uterine cavity</li>
				<li><strong>Hysteroscopy:</strong> Direct visualization and treatment of uterine abnormalities</li>
				<li><strong>MRI:</strong> If uterine anomaly suspected</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $300-$1,000 for imaging; $2,000-$10,000 for hysteroscopy</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Blood Clotting Panel</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Antiphospholipid antibodies:</strong> Lupus anticoagulant, anticardiolipin, beta-2 glycoprotein (tested twice, 12 weeks apart)</li>
				<li><strong>Factor V Leiden</strong></li>
				<li><strong>Prothrombin gene mutation</strong></li>
				<li><strong>Protein C, Protein S, Antithrombin III</strong></li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $500-$2,000</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Hormonal Testing</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>TSH and thyroid antibodies</strong></li>
				<li><strong>Prolactin</strong></li>
				<li><strong>Hemoglobin A1C</strong> (diabetes screening)</li>
				<li><strong>Day 3 FSH, estradiol, AMH</strong> (ovarian reserve)</li>
				<li><strong>Progesterone</strong> (mid-luteal phase)</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $200-$800</p>
		</div>

		<h3>Additional Testing (Case-by-Case)</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Endometrial biopsy:</strong> Check for chronic endometritis (infection)</li>
			<li><strong>Sperm DNA fragmentation:</strong> If male factor suspected</li>
			<li><strong>ERA (Endometrial Receptivity Analysis):</strong> Timing of implantation window</li>
			<li><strong>Immunological panels:</strong> NK cells, cytokines (controversial, not universally recommended)</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="warning-box">
			<strong>Note on immune testing:</strong> Testing for natural killer cells, cytokines, and other immune factors is controversial. Many reproductive immunology treatments lack strong evidence. Discuss thoroughly with your doctor before pursuing expensive immune protocols.
		</div>

		<h2>Treatment Options</h2>

		<h3>Based on Identified Cause</h3>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)</h4>
			<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Low-dose aspirin (81mg daily) + heparin or Lovenox injections throughout pregnancy</p>
			<p><strong>Success rate:</strong> 70-80% live birth rate with treatment (vs. 10-20% without)</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $100-$500/month for medications</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Uterine Abnormalities</h4>
			<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Surgical correction via hysteroscopy</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Septum resection</li>
				<li>Fibroid removal (myomectomy)</li>
				<li>Adhesion removal (for Asherman's)</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Success rate:</strong> Varies by condition; septum removal significantly improves outcomes</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $5,000-$15,000</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Parental Chromosomal Translocation</h4>
			<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> IVF with PGT-SR (preimplantation genetic testing for structural rearrangements)</p>
			<p>This tests embryos before transfer to select those with normal chromosomes.</p>
			<p><strong>Success rate:</strong> Significantly reduces miscarriage risk</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $20,000-$35,000 per IVF cycle with testing</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Thyroid Dysfunction</h4>
			<p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Thyroid medication (levothyroxine) to normalize TSH</p>
			<p><strong>Goal:</strong> TSH below 2.5 mIU/L during pregnancy</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $10-$50/month</p>
		</div>

		<h3>Empiric Treatments (When Cause Unknown)</h3>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Progesterone Supplementation</h4>
			<p>Vaginal or intramuscular progesterone starting after ovulation or positive pregnancy test.</p>
			<p><strong>Evidence:</strong> PRISM trial showed benefit for women with bleeding in early pregnancy and history of loss</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $50-$300/month</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>Baby Aspirin (81mg)</h4>
			<p>Often prescribed empirically even without diagnosed APS.</p>
			<p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Low risk, may have modest benefit</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$10/month</p>
		</div>

		<div class="card">
			<h4>IVF with PGT-A</h4>
			<p>Testing embryos for chromosomal abnormalities before transfer to reduce miscarriage from aneuploidy.</p>
			<p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Can reduce miscarriage rate per transfer, especially for women over 35</p>
			<p><strong>Cost:</strong> $20,000-$30,000</p>
		</div>

		<h2>When to Consider Other Options</h2>

		<h3>Donor Eggs</h3>
		<p>Consider if:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Multiple losses with chromosomally abnormal embryos</li>
			<li>Advanced maternal age (40+) with RPL</li>
			<li>PGT-A shows most/all embryos are abnormal</li>
			<li>Diminished ovarian reserve</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Gestational Carrier (Surrogate)</h3>
		<p>Consider if:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Uncorrectable uterine abnormality</li>
			<li>Multiple losses despite normal embryos (possible implantation or uterine factor)</li>
			<li>Medical conditions making pregnancy dangerous</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Emotional Support</h2>
		<p>Recurrent loss is emotionally devastating. Consider:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Counseling:</strong> Individual or couples therapy with someone experienced in pregnancy loss</li>
			<li><strong>Support groups:</strong> RESOLVE, local pregnancy loss support groups</li>
			<li><strong>Time:</strong> It's okay to take breaks between attempts</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="success-box">
			<strong>There is hope:</strong> Even after 3 unexplained losses, the chance of a successful next pregnancy is 60-75% without any treatment. With appropriate treatment for identified causes, success rates can be even higher.
		</div>

		<h2>Questions for Your Doctor</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>What testing do you recommend based on my history?</li>
			<li>Should we test the pregnancy tissue if another loss occurs?</li>
			<li>Do you recommend any empiric treatments?</li>
			<li>At what point would you recommend IVF with PGT?</li>
			<li>Should I see a reproductive immunologist? (Ask for evidence-based perspective)</li>
			<li>What's my prognosis for a successful pregnancy?</li>
		</ul>

